DAT-1.e is a destructive column drop on `invoices` (net_amount /
tax_amount / gross_amount), `invoice_items` (unit_price_net /
line_total_net), `payments` (amount), and `incoming_invoices`
(net_amount / tax_amount / gross_amount). The down migration re-adds
those columns at the end of each table (SQLite has no syntax to add a
column at a specific position via ALTER TABLE), so the textual
`CREATE TABLE` snapshot in `sqlite_schema.sql` differs from the pre-up
snapshot — even though the schema is semantically equivalent
(SQLite addresses columns by name).

The marker downgrades the round-trip mismatch to a WARN. The down SQL
is still executed by the harness, so syntax errors are surfaced; the
trigger-rewrite portion of the down (which restores the 0019 audit and
0021 immutability triggers verbatim) is fully exercised.

A full table-rebuild rollback (CREATE TABLE _new at original positions
+ INSERT SELECT + DROP + RENAME) was rejected: it would have to be
duplicated for four tables, every prior column-adding migration
(0009, 0013, 0014, 0021, 0022, 0023, 0024) would have to be kept in
sync with this rollback's CREATE TABLE templates, and the data round
trip is already lossy by virtue of cents-as-INTEGER being canonical
(see 0025_down for the float-precision caveat). The simpler ADD COLUMN
+ noop_down marker is consistent with 0023's precedent.
